  <div class="page-content">
    <h1>Balance Sheet Explained: Template, Formula & How to Read It</h1>
    <p>The balance sheet is one of the three core financial statements every investor must understand. It provides a <strong>snapshot</strong> of a company's financial health at a specific moment—showing what the company <strong>owns</strong> (assets), what it <strong>owes</strong> (liabilities), and the residual value belonging to <strong>shareholders</strong> (equity). Whether you're analyzing stocks, evaluating a business, or studying for the CFA, this guide covers everything you need to know.</p>

    <!-- ═══ STAT CARDS ═══ -->
    <div class="stat-grid">
      <div class="stat-card"><div class="stat-value" style="color:#4a8fe7">A = L + E</div><div class="stat-label">The Fundamental Equation</div></div>
      <div class="stat-card"><div class="stat-value" style="color:#10b981">$124.5T</div><div class="stat-label">Total US Corporate Assets (2025)</div></div>
      <div class="stat-card"><div class="stat-value" style="color:#f59e0b">1.5x–2.0x</div><div class="stat-label">Healthy Current Ratio Range</div></div>
      <div class="stat-card"><div class="stat-value" style="color:#ef4444">3</div><div class="stat-label">Core Financial Statements</div></div>
    </div>

    <!-- ═══ WHAT IS A BALANCE SHEET ═══ -->
    <h2 id="what-is-a-balance-sheet">What Is a Balance Sheet?</h2>
    <p>A <strong>balance sheet</strong> (also called a <em>statement of financial position</em>) is a financial report that summarizes a company's <strong>assets</strong>, <strong>liabilities</strong>, and <strong>shareholders' equity</strong> at a specific point in time. Unlike the income statement, which covers a period (quarter or year), the balance sheet is a <strong>snapshot</strong>—like a photograph of the company's finances on a single date.</p>

    <div class="equation-box">
      <div class="equation-title">The Balance Sheet Formula</div>
      <div class="equation">Assets = Liabilities + Shareholders' Equity</div>
      <p style="text-align:center;color:#94a3b8;margin:8px 0 0">This equation <strong>must always balance</strong>. Every dollar of assets is funded by either debt (liabilities) or owners' investment (equity).</p>
    </div>

    <p>The three components work together:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Assets</strong> — Resources the company controls: cash, inventory, property, equipment, patents, receivables</li>
      <li><strong>Liabilities</strong> — Obligations the company owes: loans, accounts payable, bonds, deferred revenue</li>
      <li><strong>Shareholders' Equity</strong> — The residual interest: common stock, retained earnings, additional paid-in capital</li>
    </ul>

    <!-- ═══ VISUAL BALANCE SHEET DIAGRAM ═══ -->
    <h2 id="visual-diagram">Visual Balance Sheet Diagram</h2>
    <p>The diagram below illustrates how assets on the left must equal liabilities plus equity on the right. The bars are proportional to <strong>TechCorp Inc.'s</strong> sample balance sheet.</p>

