    <!-- ═══ COMPARISON TABLE ═══ -->
    <h2 id="balance-sheet-vs-income-statement">Balance Sheet vs Income Statement vs Cash Flow Statement</h2>
    <p>The three financial statements work together to give a complete picture of a company's finances. Here's how they compare:</p>

    <div class="comparison-table-wrap">
      <table class="comparison-table">
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Feature</th><th>Balance Sheet</th><th>Income Statement</th><th>Cash Flow Statement</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td><strong>What it shows</strong></td><td>Financial position (snapshot)</td><td>Profitability over a period</td><td>Cash inflows & outflows over a period</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Time frame</strong></td><td>Specific date (e.g., Dec 31)</td><td>Period (quarter, year)</td><td>Period (quarter, year)</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Key components</strong></td><td>Assets, Liabilities, Equity</td><td>Revenue, Expenses, Net Income</td><td>Operating, Investing, Financing activities</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Core equation</strong></td><td>A = L + E</td><td>Revenue − Expenses = Net Income</td><td>Beginning Cash + Net Cash Flow = Ending Cash</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Primary purpose</strong></td><td>Assess solvency & net worth</td><td>Measure earning power</td><td>Track actual cash generation</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Key ratios</strong></td><td>Current Ratio, D/E, Book Value</td><td>Profit Margin, EPS, ROE</td><td>Free Cash Flow, OCF Ratio</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Analogy</strong></td><td>A photograph 📸</td><td>A movie 🎬</td><td>A bank statement 🏦</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <!-- ═══ KEY RATIOS ═══ -->
    <h2 id="key-ratios">Key Ratios from the Balance Sheet</h2>
    <p>Balance sheet ratios reveal a company's <strong>liquidity</strong>, <strong>leverage</strong>, and <strong>intrinsic value</strong>. Here are the four most important ones:</p>

    <div class="ratios-explained">
      <div class="ratio-explain-card">
        <h3>Current Ratio</h3>
        <div class="formula-box">Current Ratio = Current Assets ÷ Current Liabilities</div>
        <p>Measures short-term liquidity. A ratio above <strong>1.5x</strong> generally signals a company can comfortably meet its short-term obligations. Below 1.0x is a red flag—it means the company may struggle to pay bills due within a year.</p>
        <div class="ratio-example">TechCorp: $160M ÷ $80M = <strong>2.00x</strong> ✅</div>
      </div>
      <div class="ratio-explain-card">
        <h3>Quick Ratio (Acid Test)</h3>
        <div class="formula-box">Quick Ratio = (Current Assets − Inventory) ÷ Current Liabilities</div>
        <p>A stricter liquidity test that excludes inventory (which may not be easily converted to cash). A quick ratio above <strong>1.0x</strong> is considered healthy. It's especially important for companies with slow-moving inventory.</p>
        <div class="ratio-example">TechCorp: ($160M − $30M) ÷ $80M = <strong>1.63x</strong> ✅</div>
      </div>
      <div class="ratio-explain-card">
        <h3>Debt-to-Equity Ratio (D/E)</h3>
        <div class="formula-box">D/E = Total Liabilities ÷ Shareholders' Equity</div>
        <p>Measures financial leverage—how much debt is used relative to equity. A ratio under <strong>1.0x</strong> means equity exceeds debt. Higher ratios increase risk but can amplify returns. Industry norms vary widely (utilities often run higher D/E than tech).</p>
        <div class="ratio-example">TechCorp: $140M ÷ $160M = <strong>0.88x</strong> ✅</div>
      </div>
      <div class="ratio-explain-card">
        <h3>Book Value per Share (BVPS)</h3>
        <div class="formula-box">BVPS = Shareholders' Equity ÷ Shares Outstanding</div>
        <p>Represents the net asset value per share. If the stock trades below BVPS, it could be undervalued (or the market expects future losses). Value investors use <strong>Price-to-Book (P/B)</strong> to compare market price to book value.</p>
        <div class="ratio-example">TechCorp: $160M ÷ 50M shares = <strong>$3.20/share</strong></div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ═══ HOW TO READ A BALANCE SHEET ═══ -->
    <h2 id="how-to-read-a-balance-sheet">How to Read a Balance Sheet: Step-by-Step Guide</h2>
    <p>Reading a balance sheet doesn't have to be intimidating. Follow this systematic approach to extract meaningful insights:</p>

    <div class="steps-container">
      <div class="step-card">
        <div class="step-number">1</div>
        <div class="step-content">
          <h3>Start with Total Assets</h3>
          <p>Look at the bottom line of the assets section first. This tells you the overall <strong>size</strong> of the company. Compare it year-over-year: are assets growing or shrinking?</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="step-card">
        <div class="step-number">2</div>
        <div class="step-content">
          <h3>Break Down Current vs Non-Current Assets</h3>
          <p><strong>Current assets</strong> (cash, receivables, inventory) can be converted to cash within 1 year. <strong>Non-current assets</strong> (PP&E, intangibles) are long-term investments. A healthy mix depends on the industry.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="step-card">
        <div class="step-number">3</div>
        <div class="step-content">
          <h3>Examine the Liability Structure</h3>
          <p>Check <strong>current liabilities</strong> against current assets (the current ratio). Then look at <strong>long-term debt</strong>—is the company overleveraged? Rapidly growing debt is a warning sign.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="step-card">
        <div class="step-number">4</div>
        <div class="step-content">
          <h3>Assess Shareholders' Equity</h3>
          <p>Positive and growing equity is a good sign. Negative equity means liabilities exceed assets—a potential red flag. Check if <strong>retained earnings</strong> are growing (the company is profitable and reinvesting).</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="step-card">
        <div class="step-number">5</div>
        <div class="step-content">
          <h3>Calculate Key Ratios</h3>
          <p>Compute the <strong>Current Ratio</strong>, <strong>Quick Ratio</strong>, <strong>Debt-to-Equity</strong>, and <strong>Book Value per Share</strong> using the numbers you've just reviewed. Compare them to industry benchmarks.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="step-card">
        <div class="step-number">6</div>
        <div class="step-content">
          <h3>Look for Red Flags & Green Flags</h3>
          <p>Use the checklists below to quickly identify strengths and weaknesses in any balance sheet.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="flags-grid">
      <div class="flag-card green">
        <h3>🟢 Green Flags</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Current ratio above 1.5x</li>
          <li>Growing retained earnings year-over-year</li>
          <li>Manageable debt-to-equity (under 1.0x for most industries)</li>
          <li>Increasing cash position</li>
          <li>Consistent asset growth without excessive goodwill</li>
          <li>Receivables growing in line with revenue</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="flag-card red">
        <h3>🔴 Red Flags</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Current ratio below 1.0x (liquidity risk)</li>
          <li>Negative shareholders' equity</li>
          <li>Rapidly increasing debt with flat revenue</li>
          <li>Large goodwill relative to total assets (acquisition risk)</li>
          <li>Receivables growing much faster than revenue (collection issues)</li>
          <li>Declining cash position despite reported profits</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ═══ KEY INSIGHTS ═══ -->
    <h2 id="key-insights">5 Key Insights About Balance Sheets</h2>
    <div class="insights-grid">
      <div class="insight-card">
        <div class="insight-num">1</div>
        <h3>It Always Balances</h3>
        <p>The equation A = L + E is an identity, not a coincidence. Double-entry bookkeeping ensures every transaction affects both sides equally. If a balance sheet doesn't balance, there's an accounting error.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="insight-card">
        <div class="insight-num">2</div>
        <h3>Book Value ≠ Market Value</h3>
        <p>The balance sheet reports <strong>historical cost</strong> (minus depreciation) for most assets. A building bought in 1990 for $5M may now be worth $50M, but the balance sheet shows the depreciated book value. This is why stocks trade above book value.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="insight-card">
        <div class="insight-num">3</div>
        <h3>Cash Is King, But Context Matters</h3>
        <p>A large cash balance seems great, but it could mean the company isn't investing in growth. Conversely, low cash with high receivables might be fine if collections are reliable. Always look at the full picture.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="insight-card">
        <div class="insight-num">4</div>
        <h3>Debt Isn't Always Bad</h3>
        <p>Leverage amplifies returns. A company borrowing at 5% to invest in projects earning 15% is creating value. The key is whether debt levels are <strong>sustainable</strong> and whether the cost of debt is below the return on invested capital.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="insight-card">
        <div class="insight-num">5</div>
        <h3>Compare Within Industries</h3>
        <p>A D/E ratio of 2.0x is alarming for a tech company but normal for a utility. Asset-heavy industries (manufacturing, real estate) naturally carry more debt. Always benchmark ratios against industry peers, not universal standards.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <div class="faq-list">
      <details class="faq-item"><summary>What is a balance sheet?</summary><p>A balance sheet is a financial statement that reports a company's assets, liabilities, and shareholders' equity at a specific point in time. It follows the fundamental accounting equation: Assets = Liabilities + Equity. It provides a snapshot of what a company owns, what it owes, and the residual interest of shareholders.</p></details>
      <details class="faq-item"><summary>What is the balance sheet formula?</summary><p>The balance sheet formula is <strong>Assets = Liabilities + Shareholders' Equity (A = L + E)</strong>. This equation must always balance. Assets represent everything the company owns, liabilities represent what it owes to creditors, and equity represents the owners' residual claim after all liabilities are paid.</p></details>
      <details class="faq-item"><summary>What is the difference between a balance sheet and an income statement?</summary><p>A balance sheet shows a company's financial position at a specific date (a snapshot), while an income statement shows revenues, expenses, and profit over a period of time. The balance sheet reports assets, liabilities, and equity; the income statement reports revenue minus expenses to arrive at net income.</p></details>
      <details class="faq-item"><summary>How do you read a balance sheet?</summary><p>Start with total assets, then review current vs. non-current assets. Examine liabilities (current and long-term). Check shareholders' equity. Calculate key ratios like the current ratio, debt-to-equity ratio, and book value per share. Compare trends over multiple periods and benchmark against industry peers.</p></details>
      <details class="faq-item"><summary>What are the key ratios derived from a balance sheet?</summary><p>Key balance sheet ratios include the <strong>Current Ratio</strong> (current assets / current liabilities), <strong>Quick Ratio</strong> ((current assets − inventory) / current liabilities), <strong>Debt-to-Equity Ratio</strong> (total liabilities / shareholders' equity), and <strong>Book Value per Share</strong> (shareholders' equity / shares outstanding). These ratios help assess liquidity, leverage, and intrinsic value.</p></details>
    </div>
  </div>

  <script is:inline src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/chart.js"></script>
  <script is:inline>
    (function() {
      /* ═══ BUILDER LOGIC ═══ */
      var ids = ['b-cash','b-receivables','b-inventory','b-ppe','b-other-assets','b-current-liab','b-lt-debt','b-other-liab','b-shares'];
      function gv(id) { var el = document.getElementById(id); return el ? (parseFloat(el.value) || 0) : 0; }
      function fmt(n) { if (Math.abs(n) >= 1e9) return '$' + (n/1e9).toFixed(2) + 'B'; if (Math.abs(n) >= 1e6) return '$' + (n/1e6).toFixed(2) + 'M'; if (Math.abs(n) >= 1e3) return '$' + (n/1e3).toFixed(0) + 'K'; return '$' + n.toLocaleString(); }
      function fmtFull(n) { return '$' + n.toLocaleString(); }

      function recalc() {
        var cash = gv('b-cash'), recv = gv('b-receivables'), inv = gv('b-inventory'), ppe = gv('b-ppe'), otherA = gv('b-other-assets');
        var cLiab = gv('b-current-liab'), ltDebt = gv('b-lt-debt'), otherL = gv('b-other-liab'), shares = gv('b-shares');

        var currentAssets = cash + recv + inv;
        var totalAssets = currentAssets + ppe + otherA;
        var totalLiab = cLiab + ltDebt + otherL;
        var equity = totalAssets - totalLiab;

        document.getElementById('total-assets-display').textContent = 'Total Assets: ' + fmtFull(totalAssets);
        document.getElementById('total-liab-display').textContent = 'Total Liabilities: ' + fmtFull(totalLiab);
        document.getElementById('equity-display').textContent = 'Shareholders\' Equity: ' + fmtFull(equity);

        var cr = cLiab > 0 ? (currentAssets / cLiab) : 0;
        var qr = cLiab > 0 ? ((currentAssets - inv) / cLiab) : 0;
        var de = equity > 0 ? (totalLiab / equity) : 0;
        var bvps = shares > 0 ? (equity / shares) : 0;

        document.getElementById('r-current').textContent = cr.toFixed(2) + 'x';
        document.getElementById('r-quick').textContent = qr.toFixed(2) + 'x';
        document.getElementById('r-de').textContent = de.toFixed(2) + 'x';
        document.getElementById('r-bvps').textContent = '$' + bvps.toFixed(2);

        document.getElementById('r-current').style.color = cr >= 1.5 ? '#10b981' : (cr >= 1.0 ? '#f59e0b' : '#ef4444');
        document.getElementById('r-quick').style.color = qr >= 1.0 ? '#10b981' : (qr >= 0.5 ? '#f59e0b' : '#ef4444');
        document.getElementById('r-de').style.color = de <= 1.0 ? '#10b981' : (de <= 2.0 ? '#f59e0b' : '#ef4444');

        var checkEl = document.getElementById('balance-check');
        if (equity >= 0) {
          checkEl.className = 'balance-check balanced';
          checkEl.textContent = '✅ The balance sheet balances! Assets ($' + totalAssets.toLocaleString() + ') = Liabilities + Equity ($' + (totalLiab + equity).toLocaleString() + ')';
        } else {
          checkEl.className = 'balance-check negative';
          checkEl.textContent = '⚠️ Negative equity! Liabilities exceed assets by ' + fmtFull(Math.abs(equity));
        }
      }

      for (var i = 0; i < ids.length; i++) {
        var el = document.getElementById(ids[i]);
        if (el) el.addEventListener('input', recalc);
      }

      /* ═══ STACKED BAR CHART ═══ */
      var ctxBar = document.getElementById('stackedBarChart');
      if (ctxBar) {
        new Chart(ctxBar.getContext('2d'), {
          type: 'bar',
          data: {
            labels: ['Assets', 'Liabilities + Equity'],
            datasets: [
              { label: 'Cash & Equivalents', data: [85, 0], backgroundColor: '#4a8fe7' },
              { label: 'Receivables', data: [45, 0], backgroundColor: '#6366f1' },
              { label: 'Inventory', data: [30, 0], backgroundColor: '#8b5cf6' },
              { label: 'PP&E', data: [100, 0], backgroundColor: '#a78bfa' },
              { label: 'Intangibles & Other', data: [40, 0], backgroundColor: '#c4b5fd' },
              { label: 'Current Liabilities', data: [0, 80], backgroundColor: '#ef4444' },
              { label: 'Long-term Debt', data: [0, 60], backgroundColor: '#f97316' },
              { label: 'Shareholders\' Equity', data: [0, 160], backgroundColor: '#10b981' }
            ]
          },
          options: {
            responsive: true,
            maintainAspectRatio: false,
            plugins: {
              legend: { position: 'bottom', labels: { color: '#94a3b8', boxWidth: 14, padding: 12, font: { size: 11 } } },
              tooltip: { callbacks: { label: function(c) { return c.dataset.label + ': $' + c.raw + 'M'; } } }
            },
            scales: {
              x: { stacked: true, ticks: { color: '#94a3b8' }, grid: { color: 'rgba(48,54,61,0.5)' } },
              y: { stacked: true, ticks: { color: '#94a3b8', callback: function(v) { return '$' + v + 'M'; } }, grid: { color: 'rgba(48,54,61,0.5)' } }
            }
          }
        });
      }

      /* ═══ DOUGHNUT CHART ═══ */
      var ctxDoughnut = document.getElementById('doughnutChart');
      if (ctxDoughnut) {
        new Chart(ctxDoughnut.getContext('2d'), {
          type: 'doughnut',
          data: {
            labels: ['Cash & Equivalents', 'Accounts Receivable', 'Inventory', 'PP&E', 'Intangibles & Other'],
            datasets: [{
              data: [85, 45, 30, 100, 40],
              backgroundColor: ['#4a8fe7', '#6366f1', '#8b5cf6', '#a78bfa', '#c4b5fd'],
              borderColor: '#0d1117',
              borderWidth: 2
            }]
          },
          options: {
            responsive: true,
            maintainAspectRatio: false,
            plugins: {
              legend: { position: 'bottom', labels: { color: '#94a3b8', boxWidth: 14, padding: 12, font: { size: 11 } } },
              tooltip: { callbacks: { label: function(c) { var total = 300; var pct = ((c.raw / total) * 100).toFixed(1); return c.label + ': $' + c.raw + 'M (' + pct + '%)'; } } }
            }
          }
        });
      }
    })();
  </script>

  <style>
